I have "companion object {
        val input = Scanner(System.`in`)
    }" how do I use it to get user input in other methods?

To use the `input` variable defined in the companion object to get user input in other methods, you can access it using the class name followed by the companion object name and the property name (`ClassName.Companion.property`). Here's an example:

```kotlin
import java.util.Scanner

class MyClass {
    companion object {
        val input = Scanner(System.`in`)
    }

    fun getUserInput(): String {
        print("Enter a value: ")
        return input.nextLine()
    }
}

fun main() {
    val myClass = MyClass()
    val userInput = myClass.getUserInput()
    println("User input: $userInput")
}
```

In this example, the `MyClass` has a companion object that declares a `Scanner` object named `input`. The `getUserInput()` method uses this `input` variable to get user input. The `main()` function creates an instance of `MyClass` and calls the `getUserInput()` method to retrieve user input. The input is then printed to the console.

Note that accessing the `input` variable requires specifying the companion object name (`Companion` by default) after the class name, followed by the property name (`input` in this case).
